00:17:03.570 --> 00:17:03.940
&gt;&gt; Mira Sundara Rajan: Hi.

00:17:03.940 --> 00:17:06.260
My name is Mira Sundara Rajan.

00:17:06.260 --> 00:17:08.250
I'm a professor of
Intellectual Property Law

00:17:08.250 --> 00:17:10.850
at the CREATe Copyright
Center in the U.K.

00:17:10.850 --> 00:17:14.370
and I've written a not
insubstantial book entitled

00:17:14.370 --> 00:17:17.110
Moral Rights: Principles,
Practice and New Technology --

00:17:17.110 --> 00:17:20.480
for that reason I have
a number of thoughts

00:17:20.480 --> 00:17:22.520
but at least a couple of
which I'd like to share

00:17:22.520 --> 00:17:24.890
in the limited time
that we have available.

00:17:24.890 --> 00:17:28.020
One of them is that I've been
listening with a lot of interest

00:17:28.020 --> 00:17:30.820
to these comments about
what is the public interest

00:17:30.820 --> 00:17:33.710
in moral rights, an issue I talk
quite a bit about in my book,

00:17:33.710 --> 00:17:35.010
and I think it's a key question

00:17:35.010 --> 00:17:36.640
that we need to be
able to answer.

00:17:36.640 --> 00:17:39.110
You know, we heard
from the authors.

00:17:39.110 --> 00:17:40.450
We know how they feel about it.

00:17:40.450 --> 00:17:43.990
We know to some extent how
our middle men feel about it.

00:17:43.990 --> 00:17:46.010
How does the public
feel about it?

00:17:46.010 --> 00:17:49.360
And for me the important point
that we need to remember is

00:17:49.360 --> 00:17:53.160
that all works eventually
end up being owned

00:17:53.160 --> 00:17:54.650
in a sense by the public.

00:17:54.650 --> 00:17:58.020
They go into the public
domain, all copyright works,

00:17:58.020 --> 00:18:00.740
and that idea was
expressed by Victor Hugo,

00:18:00.740 --> 00:18:03.230
who said that the true heir

00:18:03.230 --> 00:18:06.430
of any writer is ultimately
going to be the public.

00:18:06.430 --> 00:18:10.030
And I think when we think about
the issue of moral rights,

00:18:10.030 --> 00:18:11.850
it's helpful to keep
that in mind,

00:18:11.850 --> 00:18:13.850
that preserving the
attribution of works,

00:18:13.850 --> 00:18:17.630
preserving historical truth,
preserving the integrity

00:18:17.630 --> 00:18:19.650
of works that are in the
cultural domain is something

00:18:19.650 --> 00:18:21.380
that ultimately is a
matter of importance

00:18:21.380 --> 00:18:23.630
for every citizen of a country.

00:18:23.630 --> 00:18:26.880
Another issue here that
may be apt as well is

00:18:26.880 --> 00:18:29.640
that American artists
are in a curious position

00:18:29.640 --> 00:18:32.240
because when you go out of
the country with your work --

00:18:32.240 --> 00:18:33.660
Let's say you go to France --

00:18:33.660 --> 00:18:35.520
your moral rights
are recognized.

00:18:35.520 --> 00:18:37.930
And yet here in the
United States at home,

00:18:37.930 --> 00:18:39.070
you don't have the same rights

00:18:39.070 --> 00:18:40.980
that you enjoy in
foreign countries.

00:18:40.980 --> 00:18:44.460
And I'm Canadian; we
have moral rights.

00:18:44.460 --> 00:18:45.910
If I were an American creator,

00:18:45.910 --> 00:18:48.350
I think I'd be quite upset
about that situation.

00:18:48.350 --> 00:18:50.450
So, I do think that there
is some national pride,

00:18:50.450 --> 00:18:52.310
cultural pride involved.

00:18:52.310 --> 00:18:55.670
And maybe that goes to a
final interesting point,

00:18:55.670 --> 00:18:56.770
which is what we're talking

00:18:56.770 --> 00:18:58.770
about here is cultural
diversity.

00:18:58.770 --> 00:19:01.950
Well, let's not forget that
cultural diversity also exists

00:19:01.950 --> 00:19:05.820
in the law and that has been
maybe an interesting backhanded

00:19:05.820 --> 00:19:08.230
development as far as
the relative exclusion

00:19:08.230 --> 00:19:10.030
of moral rights from
TRIPS' concern

00:19:10.030 --> 00:19:13.210
because countries have
adopted moral rights in keeping

00:19:13.210 --> 00:19:16.730
with Berne and TRIPS, but
there is tremendous diversity

00:19:16.730 --> 00:19:19.690
in how different countries
have implemented moral rights.

00:19:19.690 --> 00:19:22.290
I mean literally it would be
difficult to find two countries

00:19:22.290 --> 00:19:24.940
that have done it the same
way, and you have everything

00:19:24.940 --> 00:19:27.800
from the U.K. situation, where
you have to assert your right

00:19:27.800 --> 00:19:31.270
of attribution before you can
expect to have it recognized,

00:19:31.270 --> 00:19:34.270
to the situation in
India, where rights

00:19:34.270 --> 00:19:36.620
of integrity are
protected forever.

00:19:36.620 --> 00:19:38.260
Why are they protected forever?

00:19:38.260 --> 00:19:40.560
Well, the Indian
copyright registrar told me

00:19:40.560 --> 00:19:42.820
that amendment was brought
in for a specific reason --

00:19:42.820 --> 00:19:45.750
because the interest of the
public in the preservation

00:19:45.750 --> 00:19:48.640
of the cultural domain was
considered to be so important

00:19:48.640 --> 00:19:52.810
that integrity had to be
legislated for time immemorial.

00:19:52.810 --> 00:19:54.450
So, you have so many
different approaches,

00:19:54.450 --> 00:19:56.750
and I think that at least
should be very encouraging here

00:19:56.750 --> 00:19:59.880
in the United States because
there's so much that can be done

00:19:59.880 --> 00:20:02.310
to recognize moral rights
and yet to give them a shape

00:20:02.310 --> 00:20:05.550
that makes sense in the
cultural, technological, social,

00:20:05.550 --> 00:20:08.270
economic context
here in the states.

